<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Why does fabric shrink when washed?", answer: "Most natural fibers swell when they absorb water, and the weaving or knitting tension relaxes as the yarns return to a more natural state. When the fabric dries, especially in a hot dryer, the fibers contract and the overall fabric becomes smaller. Synthetic fibers like polyester are more thermally stable and shrink far less. The first wash usually produces the greatest shrinkage, with additional smaller changes on later washes." },
  { question: "How much extra fabric should I cut for shrinkage?", answer: "If you know the shrinkage percentage from a test swatch, divide your finished target size by one minus the shrinkage as a decimal. For example, a 36 inch finished length with 10 percent shrinkage requires 36 / 0.9 = 40 inches of fabric. If you have not tested, add at least 5 to 10 percent extra for cotton, 10 to 15 percent for linen, and 1 to 3 percent for pre-shrunk or synthetic fabrics as a safe starting point." },
  { question: "Should I pre-wash my fabric before sewing?", answer: "Yes, in almost every case pre-washing is recommended. Washing the fabric before cutting locks in the shrinkage so the finished garment or quilt will not change size later. It also removes sizing, loose dye, and manufacturing chemicals. Wash and dry the fabric the same way you will care for the finished project, since hot water and dryer heat cause more shrinkage than cold water and line drying." },
  { question: "Does fabric keep shrinking each wash?", answer: "The first wash produces most of the shrinkage, typically 80 to 95 percent of the total. Subsequent washes cause smaller progressive shrinkage, especially if the fabric is dried on high heat. For critical projects like shirts and quilts, some sewists wash the fabric two or three times before cutting to stabilize the fibers as much as possible. Once a garment is sewn, gentler care reduces further dimensional change." },
  { question: "What fabrics shrink the most?", answer: "Untreated 100 percent cotton, linen, wool, rayon, and flannel shrink the most, often 5 to 20 percent on the first wash. Loose knits can shrink more than tightly woven fabrics of the same fiber. Pre-shrunk and sanforized cottons shrink much less, typically 1 to 3 percent. Polyester, nylon, acrylic, and other synthetics have minimal shrinkage of 1 percent or less. Blends fall between the extremes of their component fibers." }
]) %>

